    q: "What's the most common reason a built-in BBQ won't light in Beverly Hills?",
    a: "Igniter failure — by a wide margin. About 55% of the no-light calls we run in Beverly Hills trace to a failed spark module, a corroded igniter electrode, or a broken igniter wire. The estate-grade outdoor kitchens up in Trousdale and Holmby Hills tend to live near pool decks and irrigation, and the moisture finds its way into the igniter compartment over a 4 to 7 year window. The fix is usually a $150 to $280 part-and-labor swap done in one visit. We carry Lynx Quikliter modules, Alfresco igniter kits, Twin Eagles flame thrower modules, and Wolf-pattern igniter assemblies on the truck. Before we quote a part we test the existing module with a meter — sometimes it's just a corroded ground wire or a fouled electrode that cleans up without a part replacement, and we say so."
