    q: "Built-in vs freestanding — what's different about repair?",
    a: "Three things. First, access. A built-in grill is dropped into a stone or stucco enclosure, often with adjacent drawers, side burners, and warming cabinets sharing the gas manifold. Pulling the grill for service usually means temporarily lifting it out of the cutout, supporting the gas line, and protecting the surrounding cabinetry. Freestanding grills roll out from under their cover and the work is done in 20 minutes less. Second, gas-line architecture. Built-ins typically have hard-piped natural gas with a manifold servicing multiple devices in the outdoor kitchen — burners, side burner, rotisserie infrared, sometimes a power burner or wok station. Diagnostics for a 'one burner won't light' issue on a built-in has to consider whether the issue is the burner itself, the dedicated valve, or upstream in the manifold. Freestanding is simpler — single regulator, single manifold. Third, parts compatibility — premium built-in brands (Lynx, Alfresco, Twin Eagles, Wolf, Viking, DCS, Hestan) have proprietary burner geometry and igniter architectures that don't substitute with generic parts. Freestanding mid-tier brands have more universal parts. We approach the two builds with different diagnostic protocols."
