    <p class="section-number">05 — Recent repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Recent Beverly Hills BBQ repairs.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Four representative service calls from the Beverly Hills calendar — model, neighborhood, symptom, diagnosis, repair, and cost. Names and addresses omitted; the technical scenarios are typical of what we see in each neighborhood.</p>

    <div class="repair-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>Lynx L54PSR — Trousdale Estates</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Rotisserie wouldn't spin; estate manager flagged it Friday morning before a Saturday-evening dinner for 14.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Rotisserie motor gear-drive seized from accumulated grease ingress over 9 years of weekly use. Igniter modules tested clean; main burners healthy; ProSear infrared had visible tile wear but still functional. Recommended ProSear replacement on a follow-up visit and authorized rotisserie-motor replacement immediately.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Lynx OEM rotisserie motor replacement, slide-rail re-lubrication, full burner inspection and grease-tray clean.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost &amp; time:</strong> $360 total. Same-day Friday afternoon. Saturday dinner went forward as scheduled.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>Alfresco ALXE-42 — Beverly Hills Flats</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Three of six main burners wouldn't light; piezo clicking on all three but no flame.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Integrated igniter assembly partially failed — two electrodes had carbon fouling, one electrode had a broken ground wire. Burner tubes tested clean; gas manifold pressure was within spec. Determined the failure was electrode/wiring, not the spark module itself.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Cleaned two electrodes, replaced one electrode wire harness, verified spark gap on all six burners, pressure-tested manifold.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost &amp; time:</strong> $215. 75 minutes on-site. No major parts replacement needed.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>Twin Eagles TEBQ54R — Holmby Hills</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> "Grill won't hold temperature." Cabinet thermometer reading 350°F when set for 500°F.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Cabinet probe-thermometer drift — actual cabinet temperature, measured with a calibrated probe, was 485°F (close to setpoint). The integrated thermometer probe had drifted out of calibration after 11 years. Gas valves and burner flow tested within spec. No actual temperature failure; the gauge was lying.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Twin Eagles OEM thermometer probe replacement, calibration verification with reference probe, full burner inspection.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost &amp; time:</strong> $245. 60 minutes on-site. Saved the household a $1,200+ unnecessary valve-manifold rebuild.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>TEC Sterling FR — Beverly Hills Post Office area</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Popping sound during preheat; one of three infrared burners noticeably cooler than the other two.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Ceramic radiant tile cracked on the right-hand burner — classic TEC failure mode at year 8. Other two burners tested clean and within heat-output spec. Igniter modules clean; gas-train pressure within spec. No other faults found.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Replaced the cracked SOL-TEC-STBAS infrared burner with truck-stocked OEM-equivalent unit, pressure-tested gas connections, verified ignition and heat output across all three burners.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost &amp; time:</strong> $480. Same-day, completed on the diagnostic visit.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
